      "rationale": {
        "session_why": {
          "text": "Horizontal pressing strength emphasized through wave loading, followed by gymnastic pushing and pulling volume in EMOM format. The EMOM metcon keeps work:rest ratio favorable (15-20 sec work, 40-45 sec rest per minute) to maintain movement quality while accumulating volume. Time domain is short-medium (14 min), preventing excessive glycolytic fatigue that would interfere with strength adaptation.",
          "source": "Bompa & Haff - Periodization 5th ed",
          "url_or_ref": "Chapter 9 - Concurrent periodization model"
        },
        "movement_why": {
          "text": "Ring dips and ring rows train vertical and horizontal push/pull patterns with unstable implements, increasing stabilizer demand and core engagement compared to fixed implements. This develops coordination and balance (two of the 10 physical skills) while building structural strength. The alternating minute format allows each muscle group to recover while the antagonist works, supporting work capacity.",
          "source": "Glassman 2002 - CrossFit Journal",
          "url_or_ref": "What is Fitness? - 10 Physical Skills"
        },
        "loading_why": {
          "text": "Wave loading oscillates between 75-87% intensity across 6 sets of 3 reps. This exploits post-activation potentiation (PAP): heavy sets at 85-87% increase motor unit recruitment, temporarily enhancing force production for 3-10 minutes. The 'down waves' at 77-82% benefit from this priming effect, allowing higher quality execution at intensities that would otherwise feel heavier. This scheme is appropriate for Week 2-3 strength emphasis and requires intermediate+ lifting experience.",
          "source": "Robbins 2005 - Post-Activation Potentiation",
          "url_or_ref": "Journal of Strength and Conditioning Research 19(2)"
        }
      }
